r the first quarter and\nprobably for the second quarter. The\nindependents are certainly losing\nmoney in their effort to get business\nby offering their products below the\nlevel maintained by the Steel Corporation.\nThey are bound to have deficits\nfor the firt throe months and\nquite likely for the first six months of\nthe year.\nThe Steel Corporation is operating\nat considerably reduced capacity,\ncompared with two months ago, and\nthis will show in its earnings for the\nfirst half of 1921.\nIn the automobile and allied trades\na false impression was given by the\nreopening in the latter part of January\nof plants which had been closed\ndown in December.\nIt Is still far from clear that this\ni was the beginning of a real revival.\"\nFor the railroads, too, the interval\nfrom the 1?t of tannorv to tti(. la* of\nApril is certain to be one of very\npoor traffic statements. Failure to\npay expenses and cover fixed charges\nwill prove to have been the quite\ncommon experience when the January\nfigures are made public, and\nwhile the showing may not be as bad\nfor February and March it is certain\nto be unfavorable.\nSecurity Mnrkrts.\nThe security markets have these\nadverse things to look forward to.\nThey also will have to contend\nagainst more depressing reports for\nlast year of the type which have been\nappearing during tho last few weeks\nand which have told against the selling\nprices of individual stocks.\nIt is. therefore, difficult to see any\nground in the near future for a general\nsustained advance in tho share\nlist. Rather it looks as if there\nmight be further unsettlement in\nspecial issues of the sort that has\nbecome familiar in the trading of the\nlast fortnight.\nBut if the market has to face a\ngood deal yet that Is unpleasant in\nthe wt^y of trade news and earnings\nMonthly II\nST. N.W.\nHalf Square East, or\nge Rooms and Can I\nirage Can Be Rent- j\nent 2nd Floor for\nIN CO.\nStreets N.E. J\nRTHEAST SAVINGS BANK\n~.??w v{\n?g jr\nI#? -?W> i>\". v -t^S\nt^v~ _-?*:,.; .-jUSmb\nnfliiOTi invi,iiiii,.ri' 1i -\"--liil c\nOSKD Bl11.l)llV(i TO BE ERECTED AT\nLKETB NORTHEAST. I\nJ\nWNGS BANK\nD A NEW HOME\nI\nvt height of 22 feet, and the interior will\nbe handsomely treated ornamental plaster.\nCaen stone, marble and bronze.\nOn the west side of the banking* room\nwill l>e the office of the president, a con^\nsulfation room, ladies' room and safe deposit.\ndepartment.\ns On the east, the cashier, tellers and\nauditing department will be located,\nwhile ample space will be left for a generous\npublic foyer and lobby.\nA large vault, fire and burglar proof.\nr with safe deposit boxes, is to be located\nin the center, at the rear of the build\ning, above which will be a mezzanine\nj floor, with the directors' room and thi?\nneeded coat rooms, etc.\nn The lease on the lot will expire April\nf 1, and building operations will start ime\nmediately thereafter. It is expected that\ny the building will be ready for occupancy\na 1 by August 1.\ninfluenced\n:ross currents\nable and Unfavorable,\nMa j ority?Real\nlent Slow.\nE\nb\nstatements, it will also have much\nthat is encouraging to buoy it up.\nj There is no doubt, for one thing, that\ni conditions in the New England\ntextile mills are rapidly getting back\nto normal, that the cut in prices is\n1 stimulating new business on a large\nI enough scale to keep operations up\nI in many cases to capacity.\nSome Betterments.\nThere is no doubt, too. that the\ns retail and distributive trade is in\ns better shape than it was two months\n1 ago: that high-priced goods have been\nworked oft and the shelves cleared\nfor new buying at the reduced price\ni levels.\nThe indications are that the lowering\nof oil prices since the middle of\nJanuary have been radical enough to\nreadjust the Industry completely to\n1 the new conditions of general busi- t\nI ness. All the tobacco concerns are\ni flourishing, and their current earn-\nings Statements see it\n_ ...B u. I\ni Summing up the Wall street posl- I\ntion in relation to outside trade, the I\nmarket Is a carefully discriminating\none. It has ceased to move in any 1\nbroad way, either up or down. It is\nmarking time while the outside situa-\ntion is developing. But with stocks R\nof companies which are doing a good\nbusiness or which, having completed p\ntheir adjustment, are on the upgrade,\nthe tendency is toward higher prices.\nConversely, other stocks in a less fa- a\nvorable position will either be left\nalone, or quite likely will work lower.\nToo Maay Set* Bonds.\nThe investment section of the market\nis working out precisely on the\nlines expected. Syndicates bringing\nout new capital issues have tempo- jjj\nrarlly overdone things.\nIt was discovered a fortnight ago\nthat most of the declared oversub-\nscriptions were not real oversubscrip-\ntions at all, and that a great part of\nthe applications came from dealers\nwho were merely anxious to make a\nquick turn and get out. The market\nfor these new securities finally be- I\ncame congested, and a resting spell I\nwas necessary to allow a better dis-\nItribution to the ultimate investor.\nThe competition of the tri.lO.OOO.OOO\nof new tnn.lo -1\nr... iiuius put out since\nthe beginning of the year was keen- I\nly enough felt in the regular bond\nlist to cheek the rise there and to\nbring about a reaction. Altogether k>\\\nthe increase in the investment supply\nhas been tot) great for demand to\nkeep pace -with it, and while there 4.\nis nothing serious in this situation, 1.\nit does call for a suspension of syn- tdicate\nundertakings foY the time 4>\nbeing and for less haste on the part\nof the investment buyer for fear that j'\nhe may be missing an exceptional\nopportunity. X\nForeign Exchange*. i\nThe sharp reaction in the foreign\nexchanges toward the close of the X\nweek is set down partly to the deci- 4.\nsion of the British treasury to begin 4.\npreparations for paying interest on\nits American debt and partly it is\nanalyzed as a sequel to a speculative\nmovement which had been pushed too\nvigorously. In no wise does the y\ndownward turn reflect upon the j\ncauses which have underlain the improvement\nin the exchange markets\nsince the close of December. It still\nremains true that the British for- 1\neign trade is steadily coming back to Te\nnormal, that other European coun- \"j*\ntries are cutting down their imports 1\nand in some rases increasing their\nexports and that if the all-important\nOerman reparations question can be\nsettled tlie international business outlook\nwill appear altogether cheerful.\nThis has been the main basis for the\n1 recent advance in the exchanges and\nI it has not been weakenod by the\nlatest developments.\n(Copyright, 1921.1\nAt Vioksburg, Miss., it was once the i\npractice to fire cannon every morning\nand evening, with a view to purifying w\nthe atmosphere.\n_ _, r-rr?? -r? IMi\nEDUCATIONAL J*\nACCOUNTANCY g\n/a Offers exceptional opportunities to\nambitious men and women.\nKfSG INTER NOW FOR\nDay and Evening Classes\nI PACE INSTITUTE\n^18 O ST. H.W.. Corner >th and G Bta.\nCOLUMBIA I.\nSCHOOL of pi\nDfeAFTING 1\nRoy C. Claflin, Pres.\n14th T Sti? North 272 I\nNight Classes?Day Classes\nIndividual Instruction\nCourse in 3 to 9 Months L\nOil] at Writ* far IttMt CaUtefu PH\nENTER ANY TIME\nV\nI\nEDUCATIONAL.\n^PANKH SCHOOL OF\nWASHINGTON\nProfs, from Spain?Con versa tkmal Method,\n[tapid Progress. 1423-5 G st. u w. M. 5?85.\no?\nWashington College of Music\nTWENTY-FOURTH\nStudent Concert\nAudjtorium of Central High School\nHoliday Evening. Februarv 21st. 8:15 O'clock\nORCHESTRA OF SIXTY\n(C. E. Christian!. Director)\nand\nSOLOISTS\nTHE PUBLIC IS INVITED\nA oollcciion will be taken for the\nJunior Red Cross\nPrograms Mailed\nri4 17th St. Franklin 4491 j\nACCOUNTANCY\nLa fltlle University Course given by per\n>?n?l end class instruction. Average length j\nibont cw year.\nC. P. A. preparation. Enter at any tio?\nCoder C. P. A. supervision.\nSEND FOft C KT \\T/>